</caption>
<paragraph blockId="11.[151,1437,1787,2028]" lastBlockId="12.[151,1437,151,827]" lastPageId="12" lastPageNumber="113" pageId="11" pageNumber="112">
<emphasis box="[199,336,1787,1811]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="112">Morphology</emphasis>
. Head capsule broad with convex cheeks and vertex smooth with ~16 evenly spaced granules (
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURE 10" captionStartId="13.[151,250,1932,1954]" captionTargetBox="[420,1168,200,1917]" captionTargetId="figure@13.[420,1168,187,1917]" captionTargetPageId="13" captionText="FIGURE 10. Male MicrOphyllium haskelli Cumming sp. nov., PT [Coll. RC 16-098] (D. Burk/Indiana, USA), A: head and thorax. Male PseudOmicrOphyllium faulkneri Cumming gen. et sp. nov., HT (D. Burk/Indiana, USA); B: head and thorax; C: left antennae." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1117482/files/figure.png" pageId="11" pageNumber="112">Fig. 10B</figureCitation>
). Compound eyes large and bulbous, no ocelli. Antennae with 23 segments, long and slender with setae length that at times can be over twice the width of the segment it is protruding from (
<figureCitation box="[1078,1184,1859,1884]" captionStart="FIGURE 10" captionStartId="13.[151,250,1932,1954]" captionTargetBox="[420,1168,200,1917]" captionTargetId="figure@13.[420,1168,187,1917]" captionTargetPageId="13" captionText="FIGURE 10. Male MicrOphyllium haskelli Cumming sp. nov., PT [Coll. RC 16-098] (D. Burk/Indiana, USA), A: head and thorax. Male PseudOmicrOphyllium faulkneri Cumming gen. et sp. nov., HT (D. Burk/Indiana, USA); B: head and thorax; C: left antennae." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1117482/files/figure.png" pageId="11" pageNumber="112">Fig. 10C</figureCitation>
). Apical antennomere cylindrical with rounded apex, about 
<date box="[574,602,1895,1919]" pageId="11" pageNumber="112">2x</date>
longer than wide. Pronotum with an anterior margin twice as wide as the posterior margin, and lateral sides rather straight with a slight rim, wider rim on the anterior margin (
<figureCitation box="[1319,1423,1931,1956]" captionStart="FIGURE 10" captionStartId="13.[151,250,1932,1954]" captionTargetBox="[420,1168,200,1917]" captionTargetId="figure@13.[420,1168,187,1917]" captionTargetPageId="13" captionText="FIGURE 10. Male MicrOphyllium haskelli Cumming sp. nov., PT [Coll. RC 16-098] (D. Burk/Indiana, USA), A: head and thorax. Male PseudOmicrOphyllium faulkneri Cumming gen. et sp. nov., HT (D. Burk/Indiana, USA); B: head and thorax; C: left antennae." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1117482/files/figure.png" pageId="11" pageNumber="112">Fig. 10B</figureCitation>
). Pronotum face smooth with 6 evenly spaced nodes, a slight groove along the median plane on the anterior half along with a slight perpendicular groove. Prosternum with slight uneven granulation throughout. Mesopraescutum with slightly narrowing lateral margins marked with 3 evenly spaced tubercles and disk face distinctly raised along the median plane marked with three tubercles, the one on the anterior rim is the smallest of the three and the posterior most at least 
<date box="[406,440,224,248]" pageId="12" pageNumber="113">2X</date>
the size of the other two. Just lateral to the tubercles of the median plane are 2 nodes on each side on the mesopraescutum disk face (
<figureCitation box="[667,773,260,285]" captionStart="FIGURE 10" captionStartId="13.[151,250,1932,1954]" captionTargetBox="[420,1168,200,1917]" captionTargetId="figure@13.[420,1168,187,1917]" captionTargetPageId="13" captionText="FIGURE 10. Male MicrOphyllium haskelli Cumming sp. nov., PT [Coll. RC 16-098] (D. Burk/Indiana, USA), A: head and thorax. Male PseudOmicrOphyllium faulkneri Cumming gen. et sp. nov., HT (D. Burk/Indiana, USA); B: head and thorax; C: left antennae." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1117482/files/figure.png" pageId="12" pageNumber="113">Fig. 10B</figureCitation>
). Mesopleurae only slightly diverging with four tubercles evenly spaced (
<figureCitation box="[334,441,295,320]" captionStart="FIGURE 10" captionStartId="13.[151,250,1932,1954]" captionTargetBox="[420,1168,200,1917]" captionTargetId="figure@13.[420,1168,187,1917]" captionTargetPageId="13" captionText="FIGURE 10. Male MicrOphyllium haskelli Cumming sp. nov., PT [Coll. RC 16-098] (D. Burk/Indiana, USA), A: head and thorax. Male PseudOmicrOphyllium faulkneri Cumming gen. et sp. nov., HT (D. Burk/Indiana, USA); B: head and thorax; C: left antennae." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1117482/files/figure.png" pageId="12" pageNumber="113">Fig. 10B</figureCitation>
). Mesosternum with slight uneven granulation throughout. Tegmina (length 
<quantity box="[1339,1432,296,320]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="8.2" pageId="12" pageNumber="113" unit="mm" value="8.2">8.2 mm</quantity>
, maximum width 
<quantity box="[345,433,332,356]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.8" pageId="12" pageNumber="113" unit="mm" value="1.8">1.8 mm</quantity>
) rather small, extending to the middle of abdominal segment II. Alae (length 
<quantity box="[1319,1424,332,356]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.97" pageId="12" pageNumber="113" unit="mm" value="19.7">19.7 mm</quantity>
), well developed oval configuration, only slightly sclerotized on the exposed fold. Abdominal segment II slightly converging, segments IIIâ€“IV gradually diverging with IV the widest segment, Vâ€“X gradually tapering towards the apex. Anal segment as long as wide and with a rounded apex. Poculum projecting well into the anal segment and covering a majority of the vomer (
<figureCitation box="[538,639,478,503]" captionStart="FIGURE11" captionStartId="14.[151,250,941,963]" captionTargetBox="[175,1427,218,920]" captionTargetId="figure@14.[150,1436,193,920]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="FIGURE11.Ventral view of male genitalia,A: MicrOphylliumhaskelli Cumming sp. nov.,PT [Coll.RC 16-098] (genital plate open away from body); B: M. haskelli Cumming sp. nov., PT [Coll. RC 16-097] (genital plate tucked against the body); C: male PseudOmicrOphyllium faulkneri Cumming gen. et sp. nov., HT." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1117484/files/figure.png" pageId="12" pageNumber="113">Fig. 11C</figureCitation>
). Profemora slender with a slight interior lobe on the anterior 1/5th as a small rounded triangle (
<figureCitation box="[421,510,514,539]" captionStart="FIGURE9" captionStartId="12.[151,250,1609,1631]" captionTargetBox="[151,1410,892,1587]" captionTargetId="figure@12.[151,1435,882,1587]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="FIGURE9. Male left forelegA: MicrOphyllium haskelliCumming sp. nov., PT[Coll.RC16-098] (D. Burk/Indiana,USA); B: PseudOmicrOphyllium faulkneri Cumming gen. et sp. nov., HT (D. Burk/Indiana, USA)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1117480/files/figure.png" pageId="12" pageNumber="113">Fig. 9B</figureCitation>
). Protibiae lacking both interior and exterior lobes (
<figureCitation box="[1096,1185,514,539]" captionStart="FIGURE9" captionStartId="12.[151,250,1609,1631]" captionTargetBox="[151,1410,892,1587]" captionTargetId="figure@12.[151,1435,882,1587]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="FIGURE9. Male left forelegA: MicrOphyllium haskelliCumming sp. nov., PT[Coll.RC16-098] (D. Burk/Indiana,USA); B: PseudOmicrOphyllium faulkneri Cumming gen. et sp. nov., HT (D. Burk/Indiana, USA)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1117480/files/figure.png" pageId="12" pageNumber="113">Fig. 9B</figureCitation>
). Exterior and interior lobe of meso- and metafemora gently rounded with interior lobes slightly serrate.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="12.[151,1437,151,827]" pageId="12" pageNumber="113">
<emphasis box="[199,361,587,610]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="113">Measurements</emphasis>
[
<emphasis box="[378,418,587,610]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="113">mm</emphasis>
]: Length of body (excludes cerci which are lacking in the HT) 27.8, length/width of head 2.4/2.3, length of pronotum 1.7, length of mesonotum 1.7, length of tegmina 8.3, greatest width of tegmina 1.8, length of alae 19.7, greatest width of abdomen 5.9, length of profemora 5.1, length of mesofemora 4.8, length of metafemora 5.4, length of protibiae 3.9, length of mesotibiae 3.6, length of metatibiae 4.5, length of protarsi 5.1, length of antennae 20.1.
</paragraph>
